Run #: A number an IAA branch assigns to each vehicle in a particular sale. This number is intended to make it easier to follow vehicles of interest in a specific sale. \10\10Sample: “Run #: 10”could reference a stock you are interested in at an auction this week. If this stock were to be re-run next week it might have “Run #: 15”assigned to it but the stock # would remain the same. \10\10Tip: Run #s are displayed 2 business days prior to an auction but can still change. We recommend reviewing the Run # the day of the auction. \10\10Lane: Some of IAA’s branches run 2 or more lanes for their sale. The first lane is referenced with an“A”.The second lane is referenced with a “B” and so forth. \10\10Sample: If “Run #:45” is in the auction’s second lane then you will see it referenced as “Lane:B Run #: 45”. \10\10Tip: Know the lanes of the vehicles you are interested in before bidding live online or live in person. It will enable you to select the correct auction lane when bidding online and, the correct auctioneer when attending the sale at the branch. \10\10Actual Cash Value: The estimated retail price of the item in its pre-damage condition that the Seller has provided to IAA. This amount is not a guarantee of the value of the vehicle. \10\10Estimated Repair Cost: The cost of repair that the Seller has provided to IAA, based on the Sellers research and calculations. The estimate is not a guarantee of total costs to repair the vehicle. \10\10Title/Sale Doc: The ownership document that will be transferred to the buyer upon completion of sale. All sale documents are subject to state laws based on the state where they are issued. The sale document issued for any vehicle is the current ownership document for the vehicle and in no way does it represent or attempt to represent any prior title history of the vehicle. \10\10Title/Sale Doc Brand: The type of title. Some examples are “Duplicate” or “Parts Only”. The brands and the criteria used to assign them vary widely from one state to another. \10\10Title/Sale Doc Notes: Special notes provided by the IAA branch that handled the title/sale document. This section may indicate important information that can impact how the vehicle can be sold. \10\10Stock #: A unique number IAA assigns to each vehicle. This 7-8 digit number can be used to identify a vehicle before, during and after the auction. \10\10Tip: Enter the stock number in the site’s keyword search box to quickly find the status of a vehicle.

The Seller has until 12:00PM noon branch time the day after the auction to either accept or decline your winning bid amount.

Once the seller accepts or declines your winning bid amount, the vehicle will be moved out of Award Pending status.\10

If the Seller accepts your winning bid amount, the vehicle will be moved to your To Be Paid list.

If the Seller declines your winning bid amount, the vehicle will be removed from your Award Pending list and no further action will be taken.

Each negotiation period expires at 8:00 pm branch local time on the sale date.
Negotiation starts when the seller sends you a counter offer based on your high bid.
Once negotiation starts, you can keep your bid, buy the vehicle for the seller\'s offer, or raise your bid to a custom amount.
If you counter the seller\'s offer, the seller can accept it or send you a final counter offer.
The negotiation ends when either side accepts an offer or the expiration time is reached.
